### Reflection

One surprising result was how differently the models interpreted the same cybersecurity alerts.  
The sentiment model labeled every record as negative, which shows that sentiment analysis is not very useful for security event classification.

The zero-shot model produced more meaningful categories such as “possible anomaly” and “routine activity,” which better matched the intent of the alerts.  

The NER model often returned no entities because the logs contained mostly technical information rather than names of people or organizations.
Even with the updated instructions, it just struggled overall and really messed up the workflow which took a lot of time to fix. 
However, the updated instructions made Groq LLM more useful than zero shot which is my orignal choice before the updated instructions.

The Groq LLM produced the most useful classifications because it evaluated the alerts based on severity levels such as informational, medium, and critical.  
Overall, this comparison showed that zero-shot classification and LLM reasoning are much more useful for analyzing cybersecurity alerts than basic sentiment models.
